  &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: 400 !important; font-size: 1.3em !important; color: #000;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;üåê &lt;/span&gt;¬†&lt;a href="https://frontendfoc.us/link/179172/rss" title="developer.chrome.com" style=" color: #D94306;"&gt;Introducing the &amp;lt;&lt;code&gt;geolocation&lt;/code&gt;&amp;gt; Element&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; ‚Äî As of Chrome 144, you can now use a new semantic &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;geolocation&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; HTML control for requesting user location data, moving away from a JavaScript-triggered prompt. There‚Äôs a &lt;a href="https://frontendfoc.us/link/179173/rss" style=" color: #D94306;"&gt;Chrome-only demo here&lt;/a&gt;. There is cross-browser interest in this approach, but some concerns and issues remain ‚Äî so keep in mind it‚Äôs not a global standard just yet, though there &lt;a href="https://frontendfoc.us/link/179247/rss" style=" color: #D94306;"&gt;is a¬†polyfill.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
